ty Kilkenny, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fitzgerald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Liam, Aidan, Bridgid, Caitlin, Donal, Fitz, Fitzgerald, Ciaran, Colum, Dermot.","Irish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name <i>Gerald</i> (see   Gerald  ), ‘son of <i>Gerald</i>’. This is a very common Anglo-Norman name in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Mac Gearailt</b>. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from <i>Gerald</i> Fitzwalter de Windsor, constable of Pembroke Castle in the early 12th century, whose grandson Raymond (or Redmond) ‘le Gros’ <i>FitzGerald</i> (died after 1185) led the invasion of Ireland on behalf of Strongbow in 1170. A branch of the family held the title Knight of Glin from at least 1299–2011."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarrell","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   Fitzgerald  .","English (Kent and Middlesex; of Norman origin): variant of <b>Jarrold</b>, itself a variant of   Gerald  ."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Fitzgerald was born in 1336, in Ireland, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Murtagh Caech O'Brien in 1380, in Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1400, in Callan, Callan, County Kilkenny, Ireland, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1336–1400":"1336–1400","1331–Male":"1331–Surnud","1353–1428":"1353–1428","1336":"1336","From 1380 to":"1380","1400":"1400","Abt 1353":"umbes 1353","1353":"1353","1331":"1331","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thomond Manor, Connaught Bridge, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Orkney, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Thomond Manor, Connaught Bridge, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland":"Connaught Bridge, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Callan, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Callan, Callan, County Kilkenny, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1336–1400":"1336–1400","1331–Male":"1331–Kuollut","1353–1428":"1353–1428","1336":"1336","From 1380 to":"1380","1400":"1400","Abt 1353":"noin 1353","1353":"1353","1331":"1331","1380":"1380","1428":"1428","Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ireland, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Thomond Manor, Connaught Bridge, Kildare, Leinster, Ireland, United Kingdom":"Ire